Part 1. Trace a real SSO login

github.com  -> Service Provider
accounts.google.com -> Identity Provider
github.com  -> Service Provider 
Trust Relationship -> GitHub trusts Google to authenticate ussers and accepts Google's verification instead of checking my password itself.

1. Click the button -> Browser
2. Redirect to the provider -> Browser
3. Provider authenticates you  -> Login provider
4. Redirect back to the app  -> Browser
5. App verifies the result ->  App (Token verification inferred)
6. App starts its own session -> App (Token verification inferred)

The app believes the provider's answer because it has an established trust relationship with Google and can verify the authentication response 
that Google sends back. This allows GitHub to accept Google's proof of my identity without asking for my Google password. If GitHub did not offer 
Sign in with Google, users would instead need to authenticate using GitHub's own login system. That menas GitHub would be responsible for 
maintaining its own authtntication infrastructure, securely protecting user credentials, and managing features such as password recovery and 
multi-factor authentication.

