Part 3. Turn on real MFA

Screenshot uploaded into screenshots folder.

A password is something you know but this was a debate in class and could be argued that it is something that you have. The login code texted 
to your phone was a little tricky to think about at first but it is something you have because the phone is something you own. Fingerprint is 
something you are another popular example of this is Face ID.

In order from weakest to strongest against an attacker using today's AI tools are SMS code, voice verification, TOTP app, and passkey/hardware 
key. The weakest is an SMS code against todays AI tools this is because AI can easily replicate SMS codes they are also susceptible to phishing 
attacks. Passkey/hardware key is the strongest against AI tools because like the hint says it would be very difficult for the AI to "physically 
possess" a hardware key.

Part 4. Plan for the guide who quits

| Access held | World A: revoke how? | World B: revoke how? | If forgotten |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Admin panel login + live sessions | Disable the user's account in the admin panel. | Disable the user's account in the identity provider. | Ex-guide can still modify bookings or customer data. |
| Photo archive (shared password) | Change the shared password and tell everyone the new one. | Disable the user's identity so they automatically lose access. | Ex-guide can still view or download company photos. |
| Group chat / manifests | Remove the user from the group chat. | Discable the user's identity so they are automatically removed from access. | Ex-guide continues receiving customer manifests and internal discussions. |

At 9 guides, I think either world could work because it would not take very long to manually remove someon's access from a few systems. World A
would likely be cheaper since it does not require setting up and maintaining a central identity provider. However, at 900 employees, I would 
recommend World B becuase it is much more efficient to manage. Disabling one account removes access to every connected system, which saves time,
reduces labor costs, and lowers the chance of forgetting to remove access from one system. Although World B may cost more to set up, I think the
time savings and improved security make it worthwhile for a larger company.